    "abstract": "26 Diverse crop rotations, cover crops and the possibility of integrating livestock make organic 27 systems potentially more sustainable than other agroecosystems. Lower reactive nitrogen (N) in 28 organic systems minimizes the potential for N losses. However, addition of organic manures and 29 residues containing mineralizable N and carbon (C) have the potential to enhance nitrous oxide 30 (N 2 O) emissions. We conducted a 39 d laboratory incubation to assess key microbiological 31 drivers controlling nitrification and denitrification in long-term organic agroecosystems during 32 simulated freeze-thaw cycles. Soils were collected from two annual organic vegetable systems 33 receiving 1) mixed-compost, or 2) broiler litter and 3) an organic perennial pasture system 34 cropped to vegetables every third year. Soil microcosms amended with 15 N labelled sugar beet 35 residue or unamended were maintained at 40, 60 and 80% of water filled pore space (WFPS). 36 Significant N 2 O was emitted (4287-6138 µg kg-1 soil) via denitrification from amended soil 37 microcosms at 3 °C and 80% WFPS. Archaeal (AOA) and bacterial (AOB) nitrifier amoA gene 38 copies were affected by temperature and reactive N species during freeze-thaws. Long-term 39 organic vegetable cropping systems receiving mixed-compost additions had the potential to 40 accumulate C and immobilize excess reactive soil N (particularly nitrates) thereby improving soil 41 health and reducing N 2 O emissions. 42"
