    "abstract": "Observation of eight mother cats and their litters revealed that the previous occurrence of a kitten vocalization was associated with an increased probabil- ity that mothers would approach kittens, change to a different body position, shift their lactation position, or vocalize. Experimental study, in which the effects of kitten vocalizations were separated from other kitten-emitted cues, demonstrated that vocalizations reliably elicited approach and investigation of the sound source from mothers. Further, mothers exposed to kitten vocali- zations removed kittens from a box and carried them to the home site. Repeated testing of mothers demonstrated that these effects of kitten vocali- zations on maternal behavior remained strong across at least the first 30 days of life. It is concluded that vocalizations are a stimulus by which kittens influence their mother's behavior."
