    "abstract": "Objective – To evaluate critical appraisal tools (CATs) that have been through a peer-reviewed development process with the aim of analysing well designed, documented, and researched CATs which could be used to develop a comprehensive CAT. Study design and setting – A critical review of the development of CATs was undertaken. Results – Of the 45 CATs reviewed, 26 (58%) were applicable to more than one research design, 11 (24%) to true experimental studies, and the remaining eight (18%) to individual research designs. Comprehensive explanations of how a CAT was developed and guidelines to use the CAT were available in five (11%) instances. There was no validation process reported in 12 CATs (27%) and 34 CATs (76%) had not been tested for reliability. The questions and statements that made up each CAT were coded into eight categories and 22 items such that each item was distinct from every other. Conclusions – CATs are being developed while ignoring basic research techniques, the evidence available for design, and comprehensive validation and reliability testing. The basic structure for a comprehensive CAT is suggested, which requires further study to verify its overall usefulness. Meanwhile, users of CATs should be careful about which CAT they use and how they use it."
