    "abstract": "As part of an ongoing project to identify and assess the distribution and population status of Bornean cats in the Sabangau Peat-swamp forest, Central Kalimantan, Indonesia, data have been collected on eight species of small carnivoreas part of the general remit, including the Collared Mongoose Herpestes semitorquatus. Data are presented on species diversity and activity patterns. The activity patterns of the small carnivores in Sabangau were generally similar to those reported elsewhere, but demonstrates the possible behavioural flexibility of the Common Palm Civet Paradoxurus hermaphroditus. Of equal interest are the species not sighted despite >6,000 trap nights including Sunda Stink-badger (Mydaus javanensis), Masked Palm Civet (Paguma larvata) and Banded Civet (Hemigalus derbyanus) thus highlighting possible implications for the distribution of these species."
